pois.description: Highest peak in Yosemite, a rock climber's paradise. From Horse Creek Pass, scramble up loose terrain
pois.label: Matterhorn Peak

pois.description:
Views of the glacial canyons of northern Yosemite

Follow the class 2 talus ridge from Stanton Pass
pois.label: Stanton Peak

pois.description: Views of Mount Conness, the Cathedral Range, and Half Dome
pois.label: Peak 10,800

pois.description: Very brief class 2 talus from Sky Pilot Col
pois.label: Shepherd Crest

pois.description: Views of all of Yosemite. Leave the High Route near extensive flat area 1/2 mi south of peak's east ridge. Work up rocky terrain to the west, keeping well above Alpine Lake. At the 12,000' level join the east ridge and scramble up class 2-3 rock to the summit plateau
pois.label: Mount Conness

pois.description: Approach via gently angled south ridge
pois.label: Gaylor Peak

pois.description: Approach from the north from the trail.
pois.label: Lembert Dome

pois.description:
Views of the sharp peaks surrounding Tuolumne Meadows

Begin either from Vogelsang Pass or Vogelsang Lake, scramble to the top!
pois.label: Vogelsang Peak

pois.description: Scramble from the saddle of Blue Lake Pass
pois.label: Foerster Peak

pois.description: Incredible views of the Ritter Range, particularly at sunset with the alpenglow!
pois.label: Peak 9,988

pois.description: From Lake Catherine, ascend a long, easy slope north to the summit plateau.
pois.label: Mount Davis

pois.description:
Can be approached from the south, but requires an ice ax to ascend steep glacier to saddle.

Easier route: From Lake Catherine, ascend moderately angled glacier all the way to the saddle. Steep talus leads to the summit.
pois.label: Banner Peak

pois.description:
Route 1 (Class 3) - Leave the High Route at the bleak tarn above Ediza Lake and scramble up snow gullies and easy slabs to the glacier, which is hidden from below. Ascend the glacier until it is possible to transfer onto the rocks bordering its northern edge. From here talus slopes - sometimes buried by snow - can be followed easily to the summit.

Route 2 (Class 2) - Theodore Solomon's original route - From Lake Catherine outlet, hike along Ritter Lakes. From the southernmost lake, ascend talus fans and steep, loose chutes to the summit.
pois.label: Mount Ritter

pois.description:
Spectacular panorama!

Begin from the north shore of Minaret Lake and ascend a long, grassy slope about 1,100' to the saddle. From here turn left and scramble up talus to the summit ridge.

Alternate approach from the Minaret Mine, following the creek and then the path of least resistance.
pois.label: Volcanic Ridge

pois.description: Scramble up snowfields, gullies, and tallus to the saddle between Pridham and Riegelhuth (peak immediately to the east). From here, a talus slope leads to the summit. If snow is present anywhere on the route, wait until late afternoon when it has softened.
pois.label: Pridham Minaret

pois.description: Great panorama of Mammoth Lakes and Ritter Range
pois.label: Peak 11,348

pois.description:
Panorama is vast, but approach is tedious.

Scramble up southwestern flank. "The jagged fragments of slate are even more trying to the patience than to the shoes." -- LeConte
pois.label: Red Slate Mountain

pois.description:
Two approaches:

1. (Class 3) Walk up talus to the pass between the mountain and Peak 12,238, then scramble up loose class 3 ridge to the top.

2. (Class 2) Climb the conspicuous class 2 chute that rises above Little Grinnell Lake
pois.label: Red and White Mountain

pois.description: From Gabbot Pass, ascend a talus slope over to a wide chute on the right side of the steep buttress that diagonals down from the summit. The 200' cliff rising above the head of the chute is the main challenge: easiest route up is class 3
pois.label: Mount Abbot

pois.description: Northeast ridge offers a straightforward class 3 climb. Instead of following the ridge, wander away from it when confronted by steep sections.
pois.label: Mount Gabb

pois.description: Ascend from the top of Lake Italy: hike up seemingly endless talus to the class 3 summit rocks; best approached from the north.
pois.label: Bear Creek Spire

pois.description: Can be reached from the loose class 2 slopes above Italy Pass; keep on the northwest side of the ridge for the easiest ascent
pois.label: Mount Julius Caesar

pois.description: "easily" climbed in a few hours from the outlet of Lake Italy
pois.label: Mount Hilgard

pois.description:
One of the Sierra's finest viewpoints

Leave the route at Ursa Lake and follow a brook downstream to its junction with the East Fork of Bear Creek. From here ascend a 1500' talus slope (often covered with snow until early August) to prominent saddle between Seven Gables and northern satellite. A class 2 ridge leads to the summit.
pois.label: Seven Gables

pois.description: Reachable via southwest ridge; may need to deviate from ridge occasionally to maintain class 3 difficulty. Approach is exposed and thrilling.
pois.label: Feather Peak

pois.description: Easily reached from the saddle to the east
pois.label: Pilot Knob

pois.description:
Approach to southwest base is easy from many cross country routes across Humphrey's Basin.

Start climbing actual peak via conspicuous gully that slices up on a left diagonal and across the face to the large notch just left of the summit pyramid. Scramble up steepening trough until force to the right on narrow ledges, then climb a steep rib to easier ground immediately below summit. Useful to use rope to belay near top of trough until very close to summit.
pois.label: Mount Humphreys

pois.description:
Great views and easy ascent!

Class 2 talus ridge from Snow-Tongue Pass
pois.label: Peak 12,971

pois.description:
Difficult and time-consuming approach

Leave High Route near south end of Evolution Lake and climb up toward the avalanch chutes. Easiest route with much class 3 rock is difficult to descriptionribe; in general, begin in the left-hand chutes and end up eventually in the right-hand chutes. Final ascent of summit spire is not difficult but is very exposed.
pois.label: Mount Darwin

pois.description: "Short and easy" with great views. Leave High Route at south end of Saphire Lake and hike up into cirque to the east. After reaching basin's first lakes, work north up gentle terrain to saddle immediately east of mountain. Short class 2 scramble leads to summit.
pois.label: Mountt Spencer

pois.description: Unparallelevationd view of Mt Darwin. Several class 2-3 routes from first lakes below Wanda Lake. Upon reaching summit arête, turn right and scramble over top
pois.label: Mount Huxley

pois.description:
Virtually every major Sierra peak stands out clearly from this vantage point.

From the outlet of Wanda Lake, stroll up easy terrain to the southwest to the minor ridge overlooking Davis Lake. Continue south up this low-angled ridge until it becomes feasible to work left into a shallow basin that eventually terminates atop the Goddard Divide. From this 12,400' pass, cross tedious talus on southern flank of the divide until reaching the base of the summit pyramid of Mount Goddard; Final 800' slope requires stamina, not skill.
pois.label: Mount Goddard

pois.description: Leave the JMT at the inlet of Helevationn Lake and scramble up class 1 and 2 slopes on northwest side of mountain. Excellent panorama and view of the Palisade group
pois.label: Black Giant

pois.description: Tedious, but not difficult, ascent up western flank from Bishop Pass - lots of talus! Stunning views of North Palisade's topography.
pois.label: Mount Agassiz

pois.description: Follow narrow ridge north of Knapsack Pass. Great views of the Black Divide, LeConte Canyon, and Palisades.
pois.label: Columbine Peak

pois.description:
Only for climbers at ease on loose class 3 terrain!!

Leave the high route east of largest Barrett Lake and ascend tedious talus slope toward huge chute that drops from the U-notch, deepest notch visible to the right of the summit. Scramble up chute until about halfway to the U-notch. There, at subtle widening of chute, you are atop a bare-bottomed section of the gully. On left, follow narrow ledge curving around the corner into the next chute. Ascend until the difficulties increase significantly. Move right into the next chute and scramble up steep rock to the summit ridge. Top lies to the left.
pois.label: North Palisade

pois.description: A few hours from Lake 11,672 (lake between Cirque and Potluck passes). Ascend easy terrain north of lake until it becomes possible to enter steep-sided cirque on the left. Work up cirque, which contains talus and steep snow, to ridgecrest above. Summit is short scramble to the east.
pois.label: Mount Sill

pois.description: Leave JMT when approaching lower Palisade Lake and ascend 2000' on class 2 slabs and talus, aiming for third chute left of the junction of Middle Palisade and its conspicuous southeastern spur (count chute in the corner as the first). Scramble up steep, loose gully until it becomes steeper and more difficult, approximately 3/4 of way to summit ridge. Exit left in this vicinity and wander up complex system of ledges and gullies until meeting summit ridge. Take care on upper section as it is loose and exposed.
pois.label: Middle Palisade

pois.description: Proceed to broad saddle between Mt Prater and Split Mountain, then proceed up class 2 route to summit. Incredible views of Owens Valley, and a fantastic panorama!
pois.label: Split Mountain

pois.description: A stimulating and airy, though nontechnical, scramble from Cartridge Pass
pois.label: Mount Ruskin

pois.description: Walk around the east shore of Marion Lake, ascend along obvious creek to next higher lake, then wander up class 2 slabs and talus. Escarpment on north side of peak is most impressive!
pois.label: Peak 11,553

pois.description: Accessible by following the well-delineated class 3 ridge rising above White Pass.
pois.label: Marion Peak

pois.description: A 30-minute detour from the route. Great views of the canyons and gorges!
pois.label: Windy Point

pois.description: Fine views of the Sierras between Whitney and Evolution Valley. Easily accessible from Grouse Lake via Class 2 terrain
pois.label: Goat Mountain

pois.description: Continue up the canyon to rejoin the high route
pois.label: Virginia Canyon

pois.description: Leave the creek at 9700 feet and head north, over the saddle and down to Virginia Canyon
pois.label: McCabe Creek

pois.description: Head west, down a will-choked valley toward McCabe creek in the valley far below.
pois.label: Upper McCabe Lake

pois.description: I.e., McCabe Pass. Follow a well defined path down 700 feet to the meadowlands northeaast of Upper McCabe Lake
pois.label: Secret Lake Pass

pois.description: Follow a crude path up and left along class 2 slabs to the northernmost edge of the half-mile-long saddle
pois.label: Cascade Lake

pois.description: Follow Horse Creek all the way down!
pois.label: Horse Creek Pass

pois.description: From more level terrain near pines, traverse diagonally to the floor of Spiller Creek Canyon
pois.label: Easier Terrain

pois.description: The most logical place to leave the pass is the notch marked by the uppermost whitebark pines on Staton's ridge. Leave the ridgecrest and drop down the rocky slope until overlooking a steeper section. The next 100-odd vertical feet are class 2-3 in difficulty; scout carefully! Alternately using narrow ledges and loose gullies, wander downward, remaining on the flanks of Stanton Peak rather than on the cliffs directly below the saddle.
pois.label: Stanton Pass

pois.description: Angle toward Stanton Pass, staying above the tarns. Slabs, then talus, can be followed until meeting a system of class 2 ledges that end on the wide pass. During this final stretch, aim for a small notch seen near the highest whitebark pines on Stanton Peak's ridge.
pois.label: Grey Butte Saddle

pois.description: From here, ascend to the saddle west of Grey Butte
pois.label: Soldier Lake

pois.description: Step over the trail and continue angling toward the left edge of Grey Butte, up the canyon wall
pois.label: Virginia Canyon

pois.description: As the willows thicken and the forest encroaches, cross the stream and head right toward Grey Butte
pois.label: Willow Jungle

pois.description: Continue descriptionending on the west side of the outlet creek to avoid tangles of willows
pois.label: Shepherd Lake

pois.description: The descriptionent to Shepherd lake is not technical, but take care on the unstable slate and snow slopes
pois.label: Sky Pilot Col

pois.description: An ever-steepening talus slope leads up to the final indignity, a short but steep slope that most hikers will find offensive.
pois.label: Shallow Bowl

pois.description: Scramble up a stable talus slope to the north to a shallow bowl
pois.label: Secret Lake

pois.description: Camping is permitted north of the wilderness boundary
pois.label: Cascade Lake

pois.description: Zigzag down the spur (carefully!)
pois.label: Class II Spur

pois.description: Enjoy the views, then head west up the ridge
pois.label: Mount Conness Ridge

pois.description: From the basin, ascend north up grass-covered ramps and gullies alongside the cascade stream that originates near the ridge far above.
pois.label: Basin

pois.description: Rather than aiming for the saddle to the northeast, turn slightly left and proceed due north up a rocky slope that ends on the east ridge of Mount Conness
pois.label: Large Flat Area

pois.description: Walk through the strip of meadow separating the lakes
pois.label: Green Treble Lake

pois.description: From the Spuller outlet, follow the creek to Fantail Lake. From its outlet, walk about 300 yards downstream along a good path. One will see a sign indicating the border of the Hall Natural Area; camp anywhere east of the border.
pois.label: Campsite

pois.description:
Walk around east side of lake.
Note: No camping here
pois.label: Spuller Lake

pois.description: When the valley steepens, contour left on easy terrain, again heading in the direction of Conness.
pois.label: Steep Valley

pois.description: Drop down into a meadow and follow a "hidden" valley down to the north.
pois.label: Meadow

pois.description: Continue toward Mount Conness; soon encounter a white, slabby section of class 2-3 problems. This section quickly leads to easier terrain - gray metamorphic rock sprinkled with dwarfed whitebark pines.
pois.label: Snow Field

pois.description: Descend about 125 vertical feet from Mine Shaft Pass to a drop off, then move left onto a reddish colored bench below an all-year snowfield.
pois.label: Below Mine Shaft Pass

pois.description: Contour northwest from the Great Sierra Mine, keeping well above the tarn. The saddle is characterized by a small but distinct red and white melange of rock right at the pass.
pois.label: Mine Shaft Pass

pois.description:
Sites lie near white outcrops about 50 yards northeast of the uppermost ruin.

Camping rules:
- Must be north of Sierra Crest
- Must be east of Hall Natural Area
- Be no more than 75 yards north of the Sierra Crest (private property past that point)
pois.label: Legal Campsite

pois.description: Take the prominent path north to the mines
pois.label: Upper Gaylor Lake

pois.description: Note: No camping is allowed in this region
pois.label: Granite Lakes

pois.description: May also pass over ridge here. Only safe to descriptionend steep northern chute late in the season when the snow is gone.
pois.label: Mount Ansel Adams Chute

pois.description: Continue down the Lyell Fork Meadow and rejoin the high route downstream.
pois.label: Lyell Fork

pois.description: Cross the ridgeline and drop down into the Lyell Fork canyon; only safe to descriptionend steep northern chute late in the season when the snow is gone.
pois.label: Electra Peak

pois.description: This alternate should only be attempted late in the season and by experienced talus walkers. From the dark bluff, contour north into the huge basin
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: Turn left and drop down the forested bluffs to the trail below. Careful - the trail is not prominent here.
pois.label: Forested Bluffs

pois.description: To the left of Foerster Peak (has a serrated edge) and to the right of a brown, U-shaped notch.
pois.label: Blue Lake Pass

pois.description: Ascend slabs along the south fork to Blue Lake
pois.label: Bench Canyon

pois.description: Wildflowers galore!
pois.label: Fairyland

pois.description: A moderate descriptionent from the dark bluff leads down to Bench Canyon
pois.label: Dark Bluff

pois.description: Ascend the hillside to the west until level with peak 3125m, then contour straight across medium size talus until reaching a dark bluff.
pois.label: Pleasant Basin

pois.description: This area is completely untouched; make sure to consult the map often as hikers frequently get lost here! Follow the valley and skirt the ridge to reach the lake at 3100m.
pois.label: Wilderness

pois.description: The only way across is to wade.
pois.label: River Crossing

pois.description: From here, climb up a few feet to the North, then follow a rough path that leads 100 yards along a bench before dropping down into a loose gully.
pois.label: Pine Grove

pois.description: Descend down to the isolated grove of pines
pois.label: Gully

pois.description: Travel north and follow a meadow corridor toward reddish cliffs in the distance. Continue in this direction for several hundred yards until it is possible to traverse diagonally down a wide gully (with a stream) on the left.
pois.label: Isolated Meadow

pois.description: Wander carefully down along the north side of the stream. Some class 3 cliffs must be traversed.
pois.label: North Stream

pois.description: Follow the main creek south from here
pois.label: Lake Catherine

pois.description: Follow the path up the bowl toward the obvious saddle
pois.label: Pass Approach

pois.description: Follow the inlet stream up and to the southwest
pois.label: Thousand Island Inlet

pois.description: Do not attempt to descriptionend the steep snowfield. Instead, move 100' east and very carefully scramble down a steep and loose defile to reach a talus slope or short snowfield. Descend to the meadowlands above Garnet Lake
pois.label: Whitebark Pass

pois.description: As soon as the first Nydiver Lake becomes visible, turn north toward Whitebark Pass, recognized by the two tiny clumps of pines not far below it.
pois.label: Abort!

pois.description: Change direction and walk toward Nydiver Lakes
pois.label: Bleak Tarn

pois.description: A nice path winds upward on the north side of the creek
pois.label: A Path

pois.description: Leave the trail about 125 yards below the Iceberg Lake outlet and cross the creek to the obvious trail on the other side. Continue along a wooded bench for about 400 yards to a gap
pois.label: Trail Departure

pois.description: Follow the trail down to the Iceberg Lake outlet - Take care not to walk on any snowfields close to the lake as they may be horribly undercut.
pois.label: Cecile Lake

pois.description: Head toward the right side of the saddle that forms the "dam" of Cecile Lake
pois.label: Minaret Lake Inlet

pois.description: In the early season, proceed around the north side of the lake to avoid snow. Later in the season, take the southern shore to reach the western edge of the lake.
pois.label: Minaret Lake

pois.description: Descend into the lush meadowlands below Deadhorse Lake
pois.label: Inconspicuous Saddle

pois.description: Avoid dropping to the meadows below. Descend unstable talus below Nancy Pass, then wander left toward the uppermost visible trees. Drop down a precipitous slope to easier ground and contour to the north.
pois.label: High Ground

pois.description: Rejoin SHR
pois.label: Tully Lake

pois.description: The talus may be tedious and loose here; area retains snow and ice well into September.
pois.label: Red and White Pass

pois.description: An alternative to the tricky terrain leading up to Shout of Relief Pass
pois.label: To Grinnell Lake

pois.description: Head down pumice-filled gully toward Mammoth Pass
pois.label: Sandy Saddle

pois.description: Continue along the Sierra Crest and descriptionend diagonally toward sandy saddle
pois.label: Ridgewalk

pois.description: Fill bottles at the northernmost Deer Lake - last water until Red's Meadow!
pois.label: Last Water

pois.description: Follow a good path down scree slopes to the uppermost Deer Lake
pois.label: Saddle

pois.description: At the pass, turn west and follow the Sierra Crest to the west
pois.label: Sierra Crest

pois.description: Circle the lake on the west to the northern-most outlet and descriptionend the tree-covered benches, keeping west of the creek and some distance from it.
pois.label: Northern Outlet

pois.description: Work down slabs and gullies
pois.label: Izaak Walton Lake

pois.description: Curve west past cotton lake to the dropoff overlooking Izaak Walton Lake
pois.label: Cotton Lake

pois.description: Lots of birds here!
pois.label: Outdoor Aviary

pois.description: Drop about 75 vertical feet and then clamber across rocky outcrops and sections of talus. Contour wherever possible, but be prepared for short climbs and descriptionents.
pois.label: Tricky Routefinding

pois.description: Spectacular views here!
pois.label: Bighorn Pass

pois.description: Leave the lake on the northwest shore near the two massive granite boulders and ascend the precipitous grassy slopes to Bighorn Pass
pois.label: Laurel Lake

pois.description: Keep west of the creek until reaching a bog at 9700'. Cross the creek and continue up the meadow to Laurel Lake
pois.label: Laurel Creek

pois.description: The path zigzags down steep, brushy, scree-covered slope
pois.label: Second Recess Descent

pois.description: A path descriptionends the north side of Mills Creek, sometimes keeping a fair distance from the creek.
pois.label: Exquisite Sierra Landscape

pois.description: Follow a path down the east side of the prominent creek, reaching timberline at Lower Mills Creek Lake
pois.label: Mills Creek Meadowlands

pois.description: Continue down path a few hundred yards and reach a fine viewpoint. Veer right, cross a short, jumbled section of talus to another valley
pois.label: Barren Valley

pois.description: From here, pick up a path that drops down a precipitous slope into a barren valley
pois.label: Sandy Saddle

pois.description: Once below the tarn, bear slightly right and descriptionend alongside a stream that slams through a wide slot. After a short distance move diagonally over to a sandy saddle
pois.label: Tarn

pois.description: Destroy all the ducks (i.e., cairns) you find!
pois.label: Gabbot Pass

pois.description: Pass on the northern shore
pois.label: Skirt Italy

pois.description: An alternative to Frozen Lake Pass. Western side has a steep class 3 cliff. Proceed down to Upper Basin and meet up with the Muir Trail and continue toward SHR
pois.label: Vennacher Col

pois.description: Stay away from creek to avoid tedious willows
pois.label: Dusy Basin

pois.description: Trail zigzags down from Knapsack Pass
pois.label: Knapsack Descent

pois.description: Meet at southeastern shore
pois.label: Barrett Lakes

pois.description: From Potluck, head north toward Palisade then aim for the inconspicuous saddle. Upon reaching the saddle, begin a gradual and roundabout descriptionent to the largest of Barrett Lakes
pois.label: Inconspicuous Saddle

pois.description: From here, ascend an inconspicuous path up a short, unpleasant scree slope lying left of the cliffs that drop from Potluck Pass. When the path fades, follow a series of narrow shelves that slant up and toward the saddle.
pois.label: Lake

pois.description: Ascend a narrow, grassy slot to top of hill, then move north until it is feasible to drop to lake
pois.label: Knoll

pois.description: Work left down a series of interconnected shelves; careful inspection will allow you to avoid class 3 climbing
pois.label: Outlet Stream

pois.description: Plenty of class 2/3 scrambling; aim for grassy cliff above. Easiest route lies at far left with talus-covered shelves zig-zagging up the cliff
pois.label: Cliff Ascent

pois.description: Head left, diagonally toward little round lake
pois.label: Disheartening Dropoff

pois.description: One of the most difficult sections on the High Route
pois.label: Frozen Lake Pass

pois.description: Follow what remains of old Muir Trail up hill to massive meadow
pois.label: Massive Meadow

pois.description: Plaque affixed to a triangular boulder
pois.label: Helevationn Memorial

pois.description: The easiest gully/chute is "on the left"
pois.label: Chutes

pois.description: Descend talus slopes to this small meadow
pois.label: Tarn Meadow

pois.description: Contour across ramps and blocks
pois.label: Rough Terrain

pois.description: Gain about 50 vertical feet, then contour around
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: Stroll pass lakes and boulders; turn east almost anywhere to reach a lovely cirque
pois.label: Upstream

pois.description: Characterized by monolithic white slabs and blocks that form a relatively level saddle
pois.label: White Pass

pois.description: Proceed upstream to this point
pois.label: Cirques

pois.description: There should be a distinct path here near the edge of the cliffs that drop down into Windy Canyon
pois.label: Windy Ridge

pois.description: Traverse around western shore of largest lake
pois.label: Horseshoe Lake

pois.description: Descend down wooded ramps; following the outlet stream is not recommended.
pois.label: Wooded Ramps

pois.description: Go around either side of the lake
pois.label: Glacier Lakes

pois.description: Stay left to avoid steeper terrain
pois.label: Granite Descent

pois.description: Contour east and then drop down to grassy meadow
pois.label: Grassy Meadow

pois.description: Go around either side of the lake
pois.label: Grouse Lake

pois.description: Copper Creek Trailhead
pois.label: Begin

pois.description: Traverse Italy Pass and meet up with SHR at Lake Italy
pois.label: Italy Pass

pois.description: Follow faint trail up through Granite Park
pois.label: Granite Park

pois.description: Pass over Sierra Crest above uppermost Royce Lake
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: Head up hill east of large falls
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: From The Keyhole, continue here to the Lost Lakes and then on to Muriel Lake
pois.label: Lost Lakes

pois.description: Cross over ridge at The Keyhole
pois.label: The Keyhole

pois.description: From here, rejoin SHR at Piute Creek
pois.label: Muriel Lake

pois.description: Cross over Alpine Col
pois.label: Alpine Col

pois.description: Easier passes (alternate to Snow Tongue) are this way!
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: Contour north
pois.label: Polished Granite

pois.description: Travel around eastern shore
pois.label: Brown Bear Lake

pois.description: Descend northwest, aim for willow-covered ledges down and to the right; class 4 slabs to the left...
pois.label: White Bear Pass

pois.description: Ascend complex terrain northwest past two lonely tarns to a sandy saddle overlooking White Bear Lake
pois.label: Sandy Saddle

pois.description: Incredibly panorama
pois.label: Top of Gully

pois.description: Stroll around east and north sides of Ursa lake until about 150' shy of cliffs that plunge directly into the water. Leave the lake and ascend a steep, grassy gully until it levels out ~200' above the lake.
pois.label: Ursa Lake

pois.description: Navigate around north side
pois.label: Bearpaw Lake

pois.description: Remain on east side of lakes. If snowfields bar easy progress on the east side, try the west side.
pois.label: Sandy Valley

pois.description: Scramble up steep slope next to obvious inlet cascade to sandy valley above
pois.label: North Merriam Lake

pois.description: Curve left around lush parkland, ascend a short incline immediately right of a cascade. Gentle shelves lead to Merriam Lake
pois.label: Parkland

pois.description: Descend into canyon; general direction toward large falls
pois.label: French Canyon

pois.description: Pass on western shore
pois.label: Puppet Lake

pois.description: Descend steep talus slopes to meadowlands above Puppet Lake
pois.label: Meadowlands

pois.description: Ascend NE from Mesa Lake along small creek to a tarn
pois.label: Tarn

pois.description: Keep Tomahawk Lake on the left, Lower Desolation Lake on the right; Mesa Lake is straight ahead
pois.label: Small Crest

pois.description: Step Across!
pois.label: Piute Pass Trail

pois.description: Intersect Piute Creek about 1/2 mile upstream from Upper Golden Trout Lake
pois.label: Piute Creek

pois.description: Continue up gentle, grassy gullies toward Snow-Tonque Pass
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: May get swampy here; bushwacking possible
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: More slabs - may gain or drop 50' to transition to different slabs
pois.label: unknown

pois.description: Gentle, forested slabs between 10,700' and 11,000'
pois.label: Leave Trail

pois.description: A cool geologic feature!
pois.label: Roches Moutonnées

pois.description: Lowest lake in Dusy Basin
pois.label: Begin

pois.description: Onion Valley Trailhead, parking, bear boxes, outhouse, water spigon, trash cans, 7.6 miles E of PCT mile 788.9.
pois.label: OnionValley

pois.description: Campsite
